post_text: Beginning tomorrow, all TUHSD Students will be expected to check in to all 7 canvas classes daily to ensure they have all the information they need and up to date with all assignments. Attendance is taken at all scheduled live zoom meetings. Additionally, students will be required to attend a Mandatory Live Tutorial each Friday at the time listed on the schedule. This will require them to check in live on zoom with 1 or more of their teachers to ensure that they have the support that they need. Thank you for all your feedback and support on our Distance Learning journey.

post_text: Due to Kern County being placed on the State COVID-19 monitoring list, we will be required to start school in the distance learning instructional model, thus preventing in-person instruction to begin the school year. It is TUHSD's desire to shift to a hybrid or normal schedule as soon as guidance from both the county and state officials allow for their implementation. For your reference, attached are the schedules for both our full distance learning model and hybrid model at TUHS. More information will be coming in the next few days leading to the August 13th start of school.

post_text: In the past week students, parents, and employees of Elk Hills, McKittrick, Taft City, and Taft Union High School District, have come together to create a comprehensive plan for safely returning to our campuses. Committee and subcommittees are collaboratively reviewing all areas relating to the reopening while also working with the California Department of Educationâ€™s Guidelines for reopening schools. Recommendations will be made available to local School Boards as they proceed in the decision-making process of reopening schools in their district. As your school community, our goal is to give weekly updates and continue to keep parents and students informed. Thank you for your constant support and patience during these unique times. Taft City School District Mckittrick Elementary Elk Hills Elementary

post_text: Congratulations to our Class of 2020 graduate Nathaniel Morris. Nate is the recipient of two awards from #KernFoundation.
shared_text:
Kern Community Foundation
June 10 at 3:13 PM Â·

Kern Community Foundation's #KernFutures Virtual Parade of Scholars now highlights Nathaniel Morris of Taft Union High School. The 18-year-old will be attending Fresno State and majoring in visual and performing arts. Nate is the recipient of two awards from #KernFoundation: a $500 Eunice Sears Scholarship for Music, and a $1,000 Karin Enebo Memorial Violin Scholarship. In this photo taken during his virtual orientation with our Donor and Foundation Services Coordinator, Angie Griffith, Nathaniel is posing with his bassoon, but he also plays clarinet, French horn, bass guitar, piano, organ, marimba, trombone, and other instruments. Yes, the future is looking (AND SOUNDING) very bright for him. Take a bow, Nathaniel!

post_text: Congratulations, Ulises Sanchez! Ulises was selected as the Congressional Merit Award Recipient for Taft Union High School. This is a recognition given to one graduating senior from each high school in Kevin McCarthy's 23rd Congressional District. Students must exemplify academic excellence, community service, and leadership. Ulises is an example of all three. We are so proud of you, Ulises! Additionally, Ulises got to nominate an educator that had made an impact in his life. Ulises selected Sarah Hamblin, his AVID teacher. Congratulations, Mrs. Hamblin! ğŸ’™ğŸ’›ğŸ’™ğŸ’›ğŸ’™ğŸ’›

WE NEED AND WANT YOUR FEEDBACK!

At Taft Union High School District, one of our primary goals during these tough times is to ensure that we continue to provide nutritious meals for our students. With concerns about COVID-19 and corresponding school closures, we do not want to add any anxiety for our students and their families.

We want to ensure that meal availability is ABSOLUTELY NOT one of those concerns. We've been granted a waiver from the CA Department of Education to provide meals during this time to our students and our community members ages 18 and under and we fully plan to do so. How, when, and where we do so depends on YOU.

post_text: Attention Freshman Parents: Today the TUHS freshmen class was given a tour of the Oil Technology Academy and has received an application for next year's enrollment. The Academy is a specially funded program that exposes students to Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics (STEM) careers. It is one of only 16 academies throughout the State of California designated as a Lighthouse Academy, which is an honor considering there are over 400 academies statewide! While our school focus is on the petroleum industry, many of these careers cross over to other high-demand industries such as manufacturing, automotive, construction, as well as others.
